	<idx>control:help<\idx>
	<idx>help on a control<\idx>
	<idx>on-item help<\idx>

<procedure>Mouse
<list bullet>
<item> Choose Help from the control's pop-up menu.

<figure nonumber entity=FPPopupforControl>
<\figure>

<item> !!Or!!:

	<list order>
	<item>Display the Help subpanel.
	<item>Choose On-Item Help in the subpanel.
	<item>Click the control you want help on.
	<\list>
<\list>

<figure nonumber entity=FPOnItemControl>
<\figure>


<s1 id=FPPopupMenus>To Display the Front Panel Pop-up Menu
	<idx>control:popup menu<\idx>
	<idx>popup menu for Front Panel<\idx>

<list bullet>
<item> Point to the control and press mouse button 3. 
<\list>


<s1 id=PopupMenuContents>Contents of the Pop-up Menus

The contents of a control's pop-up menu depend on the behavior of the
control and its location.

<procedure>Pop-up Menus for Main Panel Controls
If the control starts an application, the first entry in the menu is a
command that starts the application. Choosing the menu item has the same
effect as clicking the control.

<figure nonumber entity=FPPopupforControl>
<\figure>

<lablist>
\Add Subpanel\ Adds a subpanel to the control
\Delete Subpanel\ Removes the subpanel and its contents
\Help\Displays on-item help for the control
<\lablist>

<procedure>Switch Area Pop-up Menu
The switch area is the portion of the workspace switch not occupied by other
controls or workspace buttons.

<figure nonumber entity=FPPopupforSwitch>
<\figure>

<lablist>
\Add Workspace\Adds a workspace
\Help\Displays help for the workspace switch
<\lablist>

<procedure>Pop-up Menus for Workspace Buttons
The workspace buttons are used to change workspaces. Each button has its
own menu.

<figure nonumber entity=FPPopupforWorkspaceButton>
<\figure>

<lablist>
\Add Workspace\Adds a workspace
\Delete\Deletes the workspace
\Rename\Turns the button label into a text field for editing the name
\Help\Displays help for the workspace switch buttons
<\lablist>

<procedure>Pop-up Menu for Subpanel Controls
The pop-up menu for subpanel controls includes a command for making the
control the current main panel control.

<figure nonumber entity=FPPopupforSubpanelControl>
<\figure>

<lablist>
\Copy to Main Panel\Duplicates the control in the main panel, replacing
  the current main panel control
\Delete\Deletes the control from the subpanel
\Help\Displays on-item help for the control
<\lablist>


<s1 id=MoveFrontPanelTA> To Move the Front Panel or a Subpanel
	<idx>moving: Front Panel<\idx>
	<idx>Front Panel:moving<\idx>
	<idx>subpanel:moving<\idx>

<note>
When you move a subpanel from its location above the main panel, it will remain
open until you explicitly close it. 
<\note>

<procedure>To Move the Main Panel
<list bullet>
<item> Drag the Front Panel using its move handles.
<\list>

<figure nonumber entity=FPMoveHandles>
<\figure>

<procedure>To Move a Subpanel
<list bullet>
<item> Point to the subpanel's window frame. Hold down mouse button 1
  as you drag the subpanel to its new location.
<\list>


<s1 id=IconifyFrontPanelTA> To Minimize the Front Panel
	<idx>Front Panel: minimizing<\idx>
	<idx>icon: turning Front Panel into<\idx>
	<idx>minimizing:Front Panel<\idx>

<list bullet>
<item> Click the Minimize button.
<\list>

<figure nonumber entity=FPMinimize>
<\figure>

The Front Panel's window icon is labelled with the name of the
current workspace.

To restore the Front Panel window, double-click its window icon.


<s1 id=InterchangeControls>To Interchange Main Panel and Subpanel Controls
	<idx>subpanel:moving a control to the main panel<\idx>
	<idx>control:moving<\idx>
	<idx>main panel:moving a control to<\idx>

<list order>
<item>Display the subpanel.
<item>Point to the subpanel control you want to put in the main panel.
<item>Choose Copy to Main Panel from the subpanel
  <link FPPopupMenus>control's popup menu<\link> to 
  exchange the subpanel control with the main panel control.
<\list>

<figure nonumber entity=FPCopyToMain>
<\figure>


<s1 id=DropControlOnSubpanel>To Add an Application or Other Icon to a Subpanel
	<idx>Install Icon control<\idx>
	<idx>application:adding to Front Panel<\idx>
	<idx>Front Panel:adding application to<\idx>
	<idx>subpanel:adding application to<\idx>


You can add any type of icon to the Front Panel.
However, the most convenient use for this feature is adding application
icons.

<list order>
<item> Display the icon for the application or file you want to add.  It can be in File
Manager or Application Manager.
<item> Display the subpanel.
<item> Drag the object to the Install Icon control.
<\list>



<procedure>Behavior of Added Controls

When you add a control to the Front Panel by dragging an icon from File
Manager or Application Manager, its behavior in the Front Panel
depends on its original behavior. 

In most cases, clicking the control
has the same effect as double-clicking the icon in File Manager
or Application Manager.

An exception is folders. When you install a folder into
a subpanel, clicking the control opens a File Manager view of 
that folder.


<s1 id=ToRemoveControl>To Remove a Control
	<idx>control:deleting<\idx>
	<idx>removing controls<\idx>
	<idx>deleting:Front Panel controls<\idx>

<list bullet>
<item>Point to the control in the subpanel.
<item>Choose Delete from the <link FPPopupMenus>control's popup menu<\link>.
<\list>

<note>
If you delete a control you've installed, you can restore it by
repeating the installation process. However, it is more
difficult to restore built-in controls or controls provided
by your system administrator. See <xref TypesOfControls>.
<\note>


<s1 id=AddSubpanel>To Add or Remove a Subpanel
	<idx>subpanel:delete<\idx>
	<idx>subpanel:add<\idx>

<list order>
<item> Point to the control in the main panel whose subpanel you want to add or remove.
<item> Choose Add Subpanel or Delete Subpanel from the control's pop-up menu.
<\list>

When you delete a subpanel, you delete all the controls in it. See
<xref ToRemoveControl>.


<s1 id=ToReplaceControlInMainPanel>To Replace a Control in the Main Panel
	<idx>control:replace<\idx>
	<idx>replacing a Front Panel control<\idx>

The easiest way to replace a control in the main panel is to exchange it
with a  subpanel control.  If the control does not have a subpanel, you can
create one temporarily or permanently.

<list order>

<item> If the control you want to replace does not have a subpanel, create one by 
  choosing Add Subpanel from the <link FPPopupMenus>control's pop-up menu<\link>.

<item> Display the new subpanel.

<item> Drop the object you want in the main panel (for example, an application 
icon in Application Manager) onto the Install Icon control in the subpanel.

<item> Choose Copy to Main Panel from the new control's pop-up menu to put that
control into the main panel.

<item> Optional: Remove the subpanel by choosing Delete Subpanel from the Front Panel 
control's pop-up menu.

<\list>


<s1 id=ToRestoreFrontPanel>To Restore the Uncustomized Front Panel

The following procedure:
<list bullet>
<item> Removes controls you added using the Install Icon control
<item> Restores any subpanels and controls you removed
<item> Removes any subpanels you created
<\list>

<list order>
<item> Open Application Manager and change to the Desktop_Tools application
group. 
<item> Double-click Restore Front Panel.
<p>The workspace manager is restarted and the Front Panel converted to its
default configuration.
<\list>

This procedure does not affect customizations done by manually
creating or editing Front Panel configuration files; it applies
only to customizations done using the Front Panel's pop-up menus and
Install Icon control.


<s1 id=AdvancedCustomization>Advanced Front Panel Customization

Advanced Front Panel customization consists of any customization
that must be done by creating or editing a Front Panel configuration
file.

Advanced customization includes:
<list bullet>
<item> All system-wide customizations
<item> Adding, deleting, or changing controls in the workspace switch
<item> Interchanging the position of main panel controls&emdash;for example,
  interchanging the position of the Clock and Calendar controls
<item> Adding special controls such as application windows and indicators
<item> Animating a control
<item> Major layout changes&emdash;for example, adding a row to the
  main panel
<\list>

Advanced customization is covered in the <book>Common Desktop Environment
Advanced User's and System Administrator's Guide<\book>.


<s1 id=TorenameWorkspace>To Rename a Workspace
	<idx>workspace:rename<\idx>
	<idx>name:workspace<\idx>

<list order>
<item>Use the workspace switch to change to the workspace you want to rename.
<item>Click the workspace button (again). 
<item>Type the new workspace name.
<item>Type Return or click on another workspace button.
<\list>

